entry.title: [Layout] Fix DCHECK when updating visible tab IDs
entry.content:
Fix a DCHECK in tab_content_manager.cc related to the ThumbnailCacheRefactor [1]. The DCHECK is triggered during

SimpleAnimationLayout if a StaticLayout attempts to invoke

TabContentManager#updateVisibleTabIds while the SimpleAnimationLayout

is active. This happens because StaticLayout updates the visible tab

IDs both when it is shown and when a tab becomes selected (to cover

the scenario where it is already visible). This is incorrect as the

active layout is the only one that should be able to

call updateVisibleTabIds otherwise other layouts might become broken.



Prevent this by filtering Layout#updateCacheVisibleIds{AndPrimary} to

only be called when the StaticLayout is active. Also add an assert to

catch and correct any other instances of this.



This is not a problem for StaticLayout as it updates the visible

tab IDs during show() as well.



Also properly override Layout#setTabModelSelector in StaticLayout. It

is unclear why this was an intentional no-op it does not appear to

cause issues by overriding it and dates back to the great upstreaming in

2015.



[1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:chrome/browser/android/compositor/tab_content_manager.cc;drc=e502291081d7e28f852b0ac8486449d7a1c509e1;l=185

- One that is empty and signifies that the accelerator should use

SharedImage

- One that takes in a client/service texture ID and specifies that the

accelerator should *not* use SharedImage



Following the elimination of the NaCL use case and subsequent

refactorings, the codepath that invokes PictureInfo() with a

client/service texture ID is never actually invoked: the client/service

texture ID come from a PictureBuffer instance created by

PictureBufferManager::CreatePictureBuffers(), which now creates only

PictureBuffers with empty client/service texture IDs on Mac. This CL

replaces the codepath that creates a PictureInfo with a client/service

tetxure ID with a CHECK that the PictureBuffer's client/service texture

ID are empty.



A followup CL will eliminate all of the non-SharedImage code in

vt_video_video_decode_accelerator_mac.*, which is now dead.

entry.title: [//media] Hardcode kDoNotAllocateGLTextures for video decoding on Mac
entry.content:
PictureBufferManager creates textures in CreatePictureBuffers() if the

passed-in `mode` specifies that it should allocate GL textures. This

`mode` argument is always false on Mac. This CL hardcodes this fact,

CHECK()-ing that `mode` is kDoNotAllocateGLTextures on Mac and

ifdef-ing out the code that creates GL textures.



This CL is the first step in eliminating the non-SharedImage case in

VtVideoDecodeAccelerator. See the linked bug for the full plan.

entry.title: base: Patch MessagePump tests
entry.content:
The MessagePump unit tests (in their Glib and Libevent variants) both

report a read of a stack address after its disappearance, centering on

the stack value `buf`. It appears that the task posted to the

`io_runner()` can run after control flow leaves the test body, which

would result in the no-longer-present stack address being dereferenced.



The remedy is to convert the stack-local into a fixture member.



For posterity, my repro was done with the following GN args:



```

symbol_level = 2

is_debug = false

is_asan = true

```

This is because CanUseCachedRects() depends on the relationship

between the LayoutObjects of the root and the target. This makes it

possible to walk up the tree only once in

the number of sources of the final CanUseCachedRects. This is to

prepare to cache rects for implicit root intersection observers.

entry.title: [scroll-start] Add scroll-start tests
entry.content:
scroll-start[1] should set the initial scroll position of a scroller



These tests will fails until blink supports scroll-start so a

TestExpectations entry has been created for them.



Some notes on the cases covered by these tests:



scroll-start-display-toggled.html: scroll-start should not reset the

scroll position of a scroller that is toggled from display:none to

display:block (or other display: causing a layout box to be newly

created[2]).



scroll-start-overflow-toggled.html: scroll-start should not reset

the scroll position of a scroller whose overflow is toggled.



scroll-start-fieldset.html: the scrollable area of a
is

handled slightly differently from other scrollers in blink. this

test verifies that scroll start works with fieldsets.



scroll-start-root.html: scroll start should work when set on the

root/document scroller.



scroll-start-vertical-lr.html: scroll-start should work correctly in

horizontal as well as vertical writing modes.



scroll-start-with-anchor-navigation.html: scroll-start should not

override anchor navigation.



scroll-start-with-fragment-navigation.html: scroll-start should not

override fragment navigation.



scroll-start-with-scroll-snap.html: scroll-snap should not override

scroll-snap.



scroll-start-with-text-fragment-navigation.html: scroll-start should

not override text-fragment navigation.



scroll-start.html: generic scroll-start tests.



[1] https://drafts.csswg.org/css-scroll-snap-2/#scroll-start

[2] https://drafts.csswg.org/css-scroll-snap-2/#toggling-display-none

entry.title: [CDM] Fixing TestSegmentInfoDB to support new format of DB API's.
entry.content:
[CDM] = Caching Default Models.



This change update the test segment info database to support ModelSource.

Doc: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1-dpjL73J-GSwQS-Uxr7qUGYUPJpnGxaidi0BZ8WpKmM/edit#heading=h.e9574c8baaho

This is required for storing default models in DB.



The plan is to :

1. Add model source to database API and migrate callers to call the API

with server model. (doesn't break anything as this is kind of same

flow as before).

2. Implement the logic for database API.

3. Handle the callers logic to support default models.



This ensures that the compilation works. Also different clients will

have different handling for default models at different layers. So

client default models handling could be a part a other set of CLs.

entry.title: viz: win: Enable viewporter for SkiaOutputDeviceDCompPresenter
entry.content:
Viewporter is a capability that indicates an output device supports

clipping the root surface. Since the root surface on Windows is just a

normal overlay, it already supports this.



Currently, the only viewporter-specific code is letting DirectRenderer

allocate a root surface that is not the same size as the window. This

lets us avoid constantly reallocating the root surface during e.g.

resize.
